div.p:
He blames me further, for not being ashamed, or blushing to affirme, that from the times of Luther, and Calvin▪ the fairest streame of interpreters, run to water, and refresh my interpretation. No Mr. W. seeing men so bold and big fore-headed, in proclaiming untruths;
 I know no reason I have of being ashamed, or blushing for standing up for the truth. And as our Saviour faith to the Jewes, who would faine have had him denyed and retracted what he had sayd concerning himselfe and his


Father: I know him, and if I should say I know him not, I should be a lier like unto you. Iohn 8. 25. So must I say to Mr. W. in this case, that should I say otherwise concerning the judgement of the best interpreters, since Luther and Calvins time, touching the Scriptures in question, then I do, I should be like unto you, and speake what is contrary to the truth. What he speakes concerning either Socinus or Arminius, as being the first authors of my interpretation hath bin more then refuted long since; when by expresse testimonies from themselves we shewed that they lead the sense and interpretation of these Scriptures, quite another way, and (of the two) neerer to Mr. Ws. interpretation then mine. So far are they off from being the first Authors of it, that they do not admit it at al (as far as I can yet see) either frō themselves, or any other approved Author. I have named already more then one, or 7 Orthodox writers, that hold the imputation of Faith in a proper sense, and am ready to examine and scan the testimonies, with any sober, and dispassionate man whatsoever. And for his tale of Peter Ainlard, (as his Scribe surely hath mis-named him instead of Abilaird) that was gelded for his incontinencie; it is well for him that there is not a Law of like penaltie amongst us, for incontinencie of tongue, because I feare then, that Mr. Ws. manhood would be one of the first that should suffer. But for Saint Bernards 190 Epistle, out of which this Tale of a Tub, is pretended to be told, I can heare no sound of it there, and yet have layd both my eares as close as well I could to heare.
